%I A395171 #67 Jun 04 2026 17:50:58
%S A395171 2283,9,41,4,15,43689,174761,236,29
%N A395171 Smallest integer m > 1 such that gcd(m^(prime(n)*k) - 1, m! - 1) > 1 holds for each positive integer k.
%C A395171 700000 < a(11) <= 357913941, while a(12) = 25, a(13) = 41, a(14) = 64, a(15) = 141, a(16) = 53, a(17) = 2831, and so forth.
%C A395171 For several indices n such that prime(n) is a Sophie Germain prime, the equality a(n) = prime(n) holds. This is not a general rule (e.g., a(24) = 177, while prime(24) = 89).
%C A395171 If q is a prime divisor of (2^(prime(n)) + 1)/3, then m = q - 2 satisfies gcd(m^(prime(n)*k) - 1, m! - 1) > 1 for every positive integer k. Hence, every term exists (see Love's answer to "Universal solutions of gcd(n^{p*k}-1, n!-1)>1 for every odd prime p" in Links).
%C A395171 For every integer n >= 2, with m = a(n), gcd(m^(prime(n)*k) - 1, m! - 1) is divisible by a fixed integer > 1, independently of the positive integer k.
%C A395171 Furthermore, the author conjectures that, for every integer n >= 2, the value of gcd(a(n)^(prime(n)*k) - 1, a(n)! - 1) itself does not depend on the positive integer k.
%H A395171 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/510656/can-gcdnk-pm-1-hspace2mm-n-pm-11-have-arbitrarily-many-but-finitel">Can gcd(n^k +- 1, n! +- 1) > 1 have arbitrarily many but finitely many solutions?</a>.
%H A395171 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/510302/if-gcdn3-1-n-11-must-it-be-equal-to-140929">If gcd(n^3-1, n!-1)>1, must it be equal to 140929?</a>.
%H A395171 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/q/511242">Answer to: Universal solutions of gcd(n^{p*k}-1, n!-1)>1 for every odd prime p</a>.
%e A395171 a(2) = 2283 since gcd(2283^(3*k) - 1, 2283! - 1) = 140929 > 1 for every positive integer k.
%Y A395171 Cf. A000978, A005384, A393224, A395115, A395286, A395944.
